title: fanoutqa: Who were the first five provosts of the University of Pennsylvania (including any repetitions), and where were they born? (8eb84e291eb8c01c)

chat_history.content: Who were the first five provosts of the University of Pennsylvania (including any repetitions), and where were they born?

Here are the first five provosts of the University of Pennsylvania (UPenn), including any repetitions:

1. George Whitefield (1714–1770): Born in Gloucester, England, Whitefield was the first provost of UPenn from 1740 until 1745. He was an influential evangelical minister and a key figure in the First Great Awakening.

2. William Smith (1727–1803): Born in Aberdeen, Scotland, Smith was a Church of England clergyman and educator. He held the position of provost twice, first from 1754 to 1779 and then again from 1789 to 1791.

3. John Ewing (1732–1802): A Scottish-born mathematician and astronomer, Ewing served as provost from 1779 to 1789. He was born in Carnshie, Scotland.

4. Rev. John Andrews (1746–1813): Andrews served as the fourth provost from 1791 to 1810. He was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, and was a clergyman and educator.

5. Rev. John McDowell (1751–1820): Born in Antrim, Ireland, McDowell was the only graduate of UPenn to become its provost. He served in this role from 1810 to 1813.

functions.desc:
Ask a capable helper for help looking up a piece of information or performing an action.
Do not simply repeat what the user said as instructions.
You should use this to break up complex user queries into multiple simpler steps.
NOTE: Helpers cannot see previous parts of your conversation.
